      {
        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "### Answer\n\n**Hg²⁺ has by far the highest affinity for thiocyanate**, with a log K₁ roughly **7–8 orders of magnitude** larger than Cd²⁺ or Pb²⁺. This is a textbook illustration of **HSAB (Hard-Soft Acid-Base) theory**: SCN⁻ is an ambidentate ligand that binds preferentially through its soft sulfur donor to soft metal ions. Among the three metals, Hg²⁺ is the softest (large, highly polarizable d¹⁰ ion), which explains its extraordinarily strong Hg–SCN bond. Cd²⁺, a borderline-soft acid, shows moderate affinity, while Pb²⁺, which has more hard-acid character, binds SCN⁻ only weakly.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes).*",
